WEBVTT

00:01.218 --> 00:01.819
Good morning.

00:03.742 --> 00:05.244
Yes, I shaved it off.

00:06.886 --> 00:07.307
Get that.

00:09.570 --> 00:14.737
Our text for meditation this morning comes to us from our Old Testament reading in Isaiah.

00:15.098 --> 00:21.186
They were all really good scripture lessons, but like this one in Isaiah for this morning, let's begin with the word of prayer.

00:22.328 --> 00:29.618
Dear Father in Heaven, we thank you for how you call and gather us each here today to be with you, to receive from you your word.

00:29.730 --> 00:36.921
Your holy sacrament, the word made flesh, comes to us and we thank you for that.

00:36.961 --> 00:47.877
We thank you for how we can come and gather here and support each other, support each other in time of needs, support each other in time of joy, all because of the love and the mercy and the grace we receive from you.

00:48.518 --> 00:49.940
In your name we pray, amen.

00:51.081 --> 00:51.642
Please have a seat.

00:56.009 --> 00:59.634
Grace, mercy and peace meet you from God, our Father, and our Lord Jesus Christ.

01:01.378 --> 01:03.021
Your brothers and sisters in Christ.

01:03.542 --> 01:08.332
Past couple of years, we have lost three large trees in our yard.

01:09.935 --> 01:17.951
Now, a few years back, I recall telling you about another tree in my yard that, and I think the quote in the sermon was that it was dead dead.

01:19.253 --> 01:20.576
And it was a pomegranate tree.

01:21.818 --> 01:23.762
And two years later, poof.

01:24.610 --> 01:26.192
It's a beautiful life.

01:26.252 --> 01:33.260
We have more pomegranates than ever, so I have to take back the whole illustration that I made in that sermon because it did come back to life.

01:35.343 --> 01:40.589
But we lost two large jokes, and these were, two of them were very difficult for us to lose.

01:40.729 --> 01:46.576
For many years, almost all the time we lived in our house, a hammock was strung between them.

01:47.417 --> 01:50.081
And many memories were made with our children there.

01:51.322 --> 01:54.546
The trees, though, were unceremoniously filled,

01:55.106 --> 01:59.531
removed by the tree service without much emotion or connection.

02:00.372 --> 02:02.835
And I guess nor should there have been on their part.

02:04.938 --> 02:06.039
Nothing left but a stump.

02:07.781 --> 02:12.047
But for us, this meant the end of an era of memories.

02:13.589 --> 02:18.034
No hammock, no leaves, no shade, no green,

02:19.490 --> 02:33.103
No reminder of the promise of life each spring as we would excitedly wait for the new green leaves to push out or the seasons of life when the leaves would wither in fall, which I didn't like.

02:35.786 --> 02:40.310
Over all, the whole event of losing these trees was a depressing event.

02:40.551 --> 02:41.191
It still is.

02:42.893 --> 02:48.018
But today, I think I'd say I use this beautiful, effective imagery

02:48.738 --> 02:52.564
in his reading that we have today in chapter 11.

02:53.145 --> 02:54.908
And the first two verses say a lot.

02:57.011 --> 03:02.339
They read, there shall come forth a shoot from the stump of Jesse and a branch from his roots shall bear fruit.

03:03.361 --> 03:10.172
And the spirit of the Lord shall rest upon him, the spirit of wisdom and understanding the spirit of counsel and might the spirit of knowledge and the fear of the Lord.

03:11.173 --> 03:16.882
And sometimes we just read through that, but when we think about it, when we think of what a stump is,

03:17.794 --> 03:18.635
A stump is dead.

03:20.657 --> 03:26.703
I remember a stump that was vivid in my memory was a stump that we would clean fish on when I was a little kid.

03:26.843 --> 03:31.527
That we would go to this lake and there was a big stump there that we used for fish cleaning.

03:31.567 --> 03:32.188
But it was dead.

03:32.228 --> 03:33.529
We knew nothing was going to happen.

03:33.549 --> 03:35.831
There became a table sort of.

03:37.573 --> 03:47.122
But Advent is a season where we were the intent for us anyway is to slow down, anticipate as we prepare our hearts and minds for the coming

03:47.618 --> 03:49.520
of our Savior, Jesus Christ.

03:50.542 --> 03:58.211
And one of the favorite aspects of Advent for me, in addition to the hymns we sing, is to hear and retell the Old Testament prophecies.

03:59.673 --> 04:16.114
Pastor Midon and I were just talking about this last week about the lessons in Carol's service and how all of those readings are just gold and how they stir something inside of you when you start out a genesis of the fall and you go through all of the prophecies announcing and foretelling the birth of our Savior.

04:18.978 --> 04:29.775
Isaiah's prophecy speaks directly to us today, setting the wheels in motion of God's plan to make his presence known to his people.

04:31.117 --> 04:44.338
It's a message of redemption, not learned by our efforts, but for us, and gifted to us through Jesus, through the Messiah.

04:44.450 --> 04:48.975
in these two short verses, these opening verses, we kind of get the whole story.

04:50.377 --> 05:04.312
God's word through Isaiah reveals our fallen state, the stump, the promise of the Savior and the transformed lives that would follow from the redemption that we have in Jesus Christ.

05:06.575 --> 05:13.042
I love the verse, foreign Christ, what was dead is made alive and what was barren, bears fruit for the kingdom.

05:16.546 --> 05:18.889
Many of our hymns this morning kind of reflect that imagery.

05:19.710 --> 05:22.493
A shoot will come up from the stump of Jesse.

05:23.294 --> 05:29.281
In our communion hymn this morning, Lohawa Rose, very famous German hymn, we hear the story re-told.

05:30.542 --> 05:36.009
Jesse was the father of King David, and from David's line came kings of Israel.

05:36.990 --> 05:43.858
And then by Isaiah's time though, the royal, that whole royal line, that whole dynasty had been cut down.

05:46.338 --> 05:58.436
Same story, Israel's disobedience to God, their idolatry, their rebellious nature, led to exile and devastation.

05:59.577 --> 06:03.924
This mighty tree, this mighty dynasty was cut down to the stump.

06:05.185 --> 06:12.256
Lifeless, hopeless, forgotten and adored.

06:12.276 --> 06:13.778
But I like the stump.

06:14.050 --> 06:20.721
The imagery that Isaiah uses in this prophecy, it's really a mirror to our own condition.

06:24.087 --> 06:39.292
We're just getting into this in catechism now, but as Lutherans, we understand that the law of God is that which acts as a curb, a guide, and a mirror.

06:40.013 --> 06:40.594
Yes.

06:42.946 --> 06:46.091
We understand that the law of God and that exposes our sin.

06:47.113 --> 06:48.235
And the law cuts us down.

06:50.378 --> 06:51.200
It does every time.

06:52.201 --> 07:09.330
We are born into this world kind of marred by this original sin related to Adam and Eve, whose same rebellion, whose same behavior against God left humanity and us cut off from God.

07:10.882 --> 07:20.636
our intimacy and our relationship and our connection with Him was forever marred, detached, kind of freed.

07:23.380 --> 07:25.783
The hymn come now fond of every blessing, says it well.

07:27.085 --> 07:32.232
It says, prone to wonder, Lord, I feel it, prone to leave the God I love.

07:33.694 --> 07:35.316
We all have a tendency to push God away.

07:36.838 --> 07:39.442
We kind of start feeling good about ourselves and we want to

07:39.970 --> 07:42.032
Say, okay, I think I got it now, I think I got it now.

07:42.633 --> 07:46.677
And whenever we do that, God has a way of bringing us back now.

07:49.440 --> 07:57.769
Our deeds and our acts and our own selfishness leads us to believe that we kind of know the answers and know best.

07:59.311 --> 08:06.098
We have a tendency to chase after things that never last, the things in life that we put more priority into over God,

08:06.818 --> 08:15.027
all the common ones, money, power, approval, status, popularity, those things that really seem to satisfy us for at a time.

08:15.088 --> 08:25.580
But in the end, like everything else earthly, all those things that we can see, we can touch, we can feel, leave us empty and wanting more, something more.

08:27.462 --> 08:34.610
And we find ourselves on this treadmill trying to bring ourselves happiness and contentment with earthly things.

08:36.994 --> 08:49.026
And so with our eyes only on ourselves, navel gazing, we end up missing opportunities to do what we're supposed to do, to serve and love our neighbor.

08:50.767 --> 08:51.588
We don't have to look far.

08:51.648 --> 08:54.051
Our own families.

08:55.712 --> 08:59.396
They can be broken by our own personal weaknesses, our own behaviors and failings.

09:01.378 --> 09:05.842
We can run smack dab into life altering health and medical issues

09:07.202 --> 09:10.988
which takes away all of our routine, takes away all of our normalness.

09:14.634 --> 09:18.561
We sometimes live in communities that are divided and embroiled in violence.

09:20.183 --> 09:26.554
Those are those people on the edge that from the periphery that are crippled by addiction or despair or hopelessness.

09:29.198 --> 09:30.119
And we do.

09:30.400 --> 09:34.226
We feel like that stump cut off from the life God intended us to have.

09:36.130 --> 09:38.834
And we can't seem to spout that new growth on our own.

09:42.740 --> 09:46.005
The law shows us this truth.

09:46.305 --> 09:52.314
It impacts us not to crush us eternally.

09:52.334 --> 09:57.162
It's not like we get up and smack us down, but it's to drive us to Jesus.

09:58.023 --> 09:59.245
It's to drive us to the gospel.

10:00.286 --> 10:01.849
The Word made flesh for us.

10:04.312 --> 10:05.394
For from this

10:05.570 --> 10:10.056
this dead stump, God produces a tender shoot.

10:13.340 --> 10:17.085
In 1988, I had the chance to go camping in Yellowstone.

10:18.687 --> 10:21.090
It was early in the year, and it was beautiful.

10:22.312 --> 10:26.878
And if you recall, in that year, Yellowstone was devastated by forest fires.

10:27.358 --> 10:30.162
Thousands and thousands of acres burned to the ground.

10:32.258 --> 10:45.859
But I think what was beautiful about God's creation in that, amongst the ashes, the fallen timbers, the charred wood, or the sprouts shooting up, of green from the ash, from the darkness.

10:47.502 --> 10:49.545
And that's the image that Isaiah paints today.

10:49.605 --> 10:57.618
Or from the stump, God produces a tender chute into a branch that will bear fruit.

11:00.098 --> 11:01.459
and the branches in the side.

11:01.500 --> 11:06.565
Jesus Christ born of that line of David that was cut to the stump yet fully God.

11:06.605 --> 11:19.319
And later on in our reading, Isaiah describes Jesus as one upon whom the spirit of the Lord rests, wisdom, understanding, counsel, might, knowledge, and the fear of the Lord.

11:19.359 --> 11:29.650
He has no earthly kingdom relying on earthly power, but it is the divine, the divine Redeemer who is perfect.

11:30.050 --> 11:33.214
and who judges in perfect righteousness that he has.

11:34.836 --> 11:43.587
And he seems that we hear throughout Advent, he upholds the poor and puts to an end wickedness all with the breath of his mouth, the word.

11:47.632 --> 11:51.116
And I love these five words in the fullness of time.

11:52.138 --> 11:54.060
In the fullness of time, God's will was done.

11:54.120 --> 11:58.866
The prophecy was fulfilled in that little Bethlehem stable.

11:59.874 --> 12:02.777
Jesus was that shoot from Jesse's stump.

12:04.079 --> 12:12.288
And like we looked at last week in our gospel, reading came not in pomp and glory, but humility on a donkey.

12:13.449 --> 12:15.171
He lived the perfect life that we could not.

12:18.275 --> 12:23.140
And he took his refuge and his wisdom and his delight in his father.

12:25.843 --> 12:28.306
He taught with wisdom that

12:29.186 --> 12:30.487
Can I confuse the wise?

12:30.547 --> 12:34.391
He healed the sick, fed the hungry, proclaimed good news to the poor.

12:34.872 --> 12:42.119
Themes that are repeated and retold each and every week here during the season of Advent.

12:43.340 --> 12:47.244
And yet, in this season, there's a bit of a paradox.

12:49.466 --> 12:51.408
Our eyes are kind of looking at the manger.

12:51.428 --> 12:57.234
We're looking at the coming of Christ, yet we know that our eyes need to be on the cross.

12:57.794 --> 13:02.461
where Jesus, that baby bore the weight of all of our sin, where he took on sin as himself.

13:06.566 --> 13:14.858
And that acts that felled us in the law that tops us to the core, has turned upon him.

13:15.879 --> 13:26.514
He's received that punishment by his wounds we are healed through his death and his resurrection.

13:26.882 --> 13:29.426
our redemption is accomplished.

13:32.191 --> 13:36.178
This is the heart of what we talk about here, each and every Sunday.

13:36.218 --> 13:39.444
It's the heart of what we do as Christians.

13:41.808 --> 13:46.756
It's not by our merits, but by grace alone, faith alone, and Jesus alone.

13:49.521 --> 13:52.466
Our absolute joy as Christians, I think that's the next

13:52.546 --> 13:58.874
next week's candle, and our joy in living even through all of the struggles of life is the truth, is that truth to which we cling.

14:00.216 --> 14:03.220
Jesus is the branch that revives the stump.

14:03.701 --> 14:06.384
He doesn't demand that we clean ourselves up first.

14:06.404 --> 14:11.932
He comes to us in our deadness and makes us alive.

14:14.175 --> 14:17.579
In our baptism, he binds himself to us.

14:17.639 --> 14:19.602
He grafts himself to us.

14:21.186 --> 14:28.879
And here at this table, the Lord's Supper, he nourishes us with his word made flesh, with his body and blood.

14:31.303 --> 14:35.229
In his word, his living and active word, he breathes his life into our souls.

14:38.234 --> 14:41.540
But a branch will bear fruit as Isaiah goes on.

14:41.580 --> 14:45.426
And what does this fruit look like?

14:47.266 --> 14:49.109
And I love the visual we have here.

14:49.149 --> 15:09.641
Again, reflected in a lot of our hymn, we see a vision of this paradise restored, wolf with a lamb, leopard with a goat, a child leading them all, a lion, no harm, no destruction, only peace, contentment, because the earth is now restored by the Lord.

15:09.661 --> 15:15.250
The fruit that points to this

15:15.330 --> 15:18.154
this transformation to us that Jesus brings.

15:19.857 --> 15:23.662
The fruit is our lives and their service to others in Jesus' name.

15:25.065 --> 15:38.044
Not as a way to earn salvation because that's been one for us, but it's a natural, it's a natural outflow of what God pours into us each and every day through Christ Jesus.

15:40.187 --> 15:42.270
Jesus says, I am divine, you are the branches.

15:42.330 --> 15:44.754
If you remain in me and I am you,

15:45.154 --> 15:46.316
you will bear much fruit.

15:48.199 --> 15:50.062
And I guess for each of us, the fruit looks different.

15:52.346 --> 15:59.920
It's the work and the works of love that flow from us as our response, as our response from our being redeemed and forgiven.

15:59.980 --> 16:03.045
And each of us have different personalities and different ways that we can do that.

16:04.327 --> 16:08.274
But it's done with joy because we're redeemed, we're restored, we're forgiven.

16:09.506 --> 16:13.531
It means forgiving those who wrong us as Christ forgives us.

16:13.812 --> 16:19.800
It means serving those who need to be served, the poor, the lonely, the oppressed.

16:22.023 --> 16:39.506
It's living in faith and recognizing the spirit's gifts within us, using God's wisdom in our decisions, using His counsel in our words, using boldness as we witness.

16:39.906 --> 16:41.268
in our daily vocations.

16:41.308 --> 16:47.978
We've talked a lot about vocations the last few weeks, but it's so true because God gives us each differently.

16:48.058 --> 16:52.605
As parents, workers, neighbors, we bear fruit by reflecting Christ's light.

16:55.128 --> 16:58.794
And it is you and me being in all situations a reflection.

16:59.635 --> 17:07.026
Your face, your countenance, your being of the deep-rooted conditional love that is yours through Jesus Christ.

17:08.994 --> 17:10.356
Are you a reflection of that?

17:12.098 --> 17:13.240
Am I a reflection of that?

17:15.623 --> 17:20.249
To use President Newman's book title, do you struggle well?

17:23.313 --> 17:30.864
Or are you a dour cranky, unhappy, miserable soul that people walk around eggshells by?

17:30.904 --> 17:36.832
But we shouldn't be as Christians.

17:36.972 --> 17:38.514
We are joyfully rooted

17:39.010 --> 17:41.092
to the tree of life, always and forever.

17:44.215 --> 17:45.677
And it's you, it's your fruit.

17:46.437 --> 17:52.283
It's how you convey what Christ has given you inside that helps restore.

17:53.264 --> 17:56.607
It helps restore a family that needs forgiveness.

17:57.749 --> 18:00.812
It helps your community, united in service.

18:03.314 --> 18:07.218
And I think this is the piece that the Messiah that Isaiah foresees

18:07.874 --> 18:17.626
beginning here, beginning with you, with me, each of us here in this church, and finally consummated in the end when Christ returns.

18:19.889 --> 18:22.332
Our service isn't, and it shouldn't be, drudgery.

18:22.832 --> 18:23.473
It's joyful.

18:24.694 --> 18:26.717
It's a response to our redemption.

18:28.719 --> 18:33.505
Luther, and this isn't the exact quote, but good works are the fruit of faith, not its root.

18:34.326 --> 18:37.490
We serve others because Christ first served us.

18:39.714 --> 18:40.695
And yet we are sinners.

18:40.855 --> 18:44.639
Our fruit is often sometimes meager, doesn't look like much.

18:45.320 --> 18:48.704
We falter, we sin, we struggle, we produce thorns, we have bad days.

18:51.647 --> 19:00.797
But all through it, in all stages of our life, in all struggles, that branch sustains us.

19:01.638 --> 19:04.581
We abide in him through the faith he produces in us.

19:07.444 --> 19:08.946
As we journey through our advent,

19:10.210 --> 19:20.506
I like the beautiful vision that Isaiah gives us to keep us joyfully charging into all situations in our lives.

19:21.407 --> 19:25.994
And that's hard to do because we have sad days.

19:27.036 --> 19:27.977
We have unhappy days.

19:28.077 --> 19:31.042
We have days where things are not going well.

19:32.885 --> 19:38.994
But underneath it all, we have an undercurrent of joy because we know how the story ends.

19:40.098 --> 19:42.481
We know where we get our energy.

19:42.521 --> 19:43.922
We know where we get our love.

19:43.942 --> 19:49.328
We know where we get our forgiveness that is unquenchable, that gets poured into us daily.

19:54.794 --> 19:57.597
This world looks at us as Christians, and what do they see?

19:58.778 --> 20:06.546
What are you conveying in your expressions, in your countenance, in your words, in your attitude, in your optimism, or maybe lack of it?

20:07.970 --> 20:10.053
in your positivity or maybe lack of it?

20:11.155 --> 20:17.985
What are you conveying about your faith that drives you when that keeps you strong?

20:19.167 --> 20:21.391
And I think it's something as Christians that we all need to look at.

20:21.671 --> 20:24.275
Do we look like we've got the love of God?

20:26.519 --> 20:30.745
You all remember the song, you've got the joy, joy, joy, joy down in my heart.

20:30.765 --> 20:33.970
And sometimes as Lutherans, we kind of sing it with a kind of a scowl on our face.

20:36.098 --> 20:38.101
But it's something as Christians we need to look about.

20:38.141 --> 20:40.043
Look at, how do people see us?

20:40.364 --> 20:41.425
Are we different?

20:46.152 --> 20:53.261
And so from this stump, from this dead stump of our sin, rises the branch of redemption, Jesus the Messiah.

20:53.802 --> 20:57.888
And through Him, through Him, your life bears fruit.

20:58.468 --> 20:59.209
Service to others.

21:00.611 --> 21:02.674
You're putting your love into action.

21:04.386 --> 21:07.871
and you're being a messenger of peace in a broken world.

21:11.096 --> 21:23.055
And so from the last word of our epistle this morning, may the God of hope fill you with all joy and peace and believing so that by the power of the Holy Spirit you may abound in hope.

21:24.056 --> 21:24.357
Amen.

21:26.039 --> 21:31.928
Now may the peace of God which passes all understanding keep your hearts and minds in Christ Jesus until life everlasting.

21:32.809 --> 21:33.170
Amen.

